<Base title="About Candace — Ennea Evolution" description="Candace is a counselor, coach, and organizational trainer in Cache Valley, Utah. Warm and direct, she helps people and teams understand the why underneath what they do.">
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container about-hero">
      <div class="about-photo">
        <div class="photo-frame"><span class="photo-note">Photo: Candace, in real light</span></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
        <h1>People make sense.</h1>
        <p class="lead">Not eventually. Not once they figure it all out. Right now, exactly as they are, for reasons that can be found.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow prose">
      <p>I learned this in the hardest rooms first. Families contesting wills. Couples writing separation agreements. Siblings dividing a business their parents had spent a lifetime building. Even there, especially there, behavior had reasons. And when the reasons came into view, people who could barely speak to each other found their way to agreements that actually held.</p>
      <p>I see the same thing now in gentler rooms. In counseling, when someone discovers that the habit they've spent twenty years trying to break has been protecting them the whole time. In a training, when a team realizes a coworker isn't difficult, just solving for something different than they are. Different rooms, same moment: the moment things finally make sense, and change becomes possible.</p>
      <p>Everything I do grew out of that one discovery.</p>

      <h3>How I got here</h3>
      <p>I started in mediation, with a graduate certification in Mediation and Conflict Resolution Counseling from the University of Utah. I worked alongside a busy attorney's practice, taking the cases he referred my way, sitting with people on some of the worst days of their lives and helping them find workable ground.</p>
      <p>Then I discovered the Enneagram, and began bringing it into that work. The difference was hard to miss. When I could help one person genuinely understand what the other was protecting, negotiations that had been stuck for months started to move. Agreements got easier to reach, and easier to keep.</p>
      <p>And then something I didn't plan: people began asking to keep working with me after the mediation ended; not about the contract, but about their marriage, their family, their own lives. They wanted the thing the mediation had given them: to finally understand what was actually going on. That became the heart of my practice. For the past eight years I've worked as a counselor and coach, doing deep individual work with people who want to understand their own lives.</p>
      <p>The company work grew the same way, by people asking. A team here, a leadership group there, and it has grown every year since. It helps that I've lived on the company side of the table. My husband and I have started, run, and sold businesses of our own, and we ran them on these principles long before I had formal names for them. So when I walk into a company, I'm not carrying theory into someone else's world. I'm back in mine.</p>

      <h3>What it's like to work with me</h3>
      <p>I'm warm, and I'm direct, and I've never found those to be in conflict.</p>
      <p>I'll tell you the truth kindly. I won't perform neutrality when I see something clearly, and I won't pretend to see clearly when I don't. I ask real questions, and I can sit with real answers, including the messy ones, especially the messy ones.</p>
      <p>I've never been very interested in deciding whether people are right or wrong. I've always been far more interested in understanding why what they're doing makes so much sense to them. That's where the change is, and it's a calmer, more honest place to work from than judgment ever was.</p>
      <p>And I'm practical. Insight that doesn't change your Tuesday isn't finished yet. Whether I'm working with one person or a leadership team, the work isn't done when it's understood. It's done when it holds.</p>

      <h3>Training and background</h3>
      <p>I work as a counselor and coach rather than a licensed therapist. That's an intentional choice: it lets me work with clients across state lines, and blend therapeutic depth with practical, real-world application.</p>
      <p>My background includes graduate training in Mediation and Conflict Resolution Counseling through the University of Utah, undergraduate studies in psychology at Utah State University, and certifications in Internal Family Systems, Coherence Therapy, and the Enneagram, along with additional training in trauma-informed care and Compassionate Inquiry. On the organizational side, I've spent years facilitating communication and leadership development across healthcare, insurance, technology, real estate, and HR, while guest-lecturing for graduate students in Utah State University's HR program and building the trainings and materials that support this work.</p>

      <h3>The short version of me</h3>
      <p>I've been married for nearly three decades, and we've raised four children, so most of what I know about people was tested at my own kitchen table long before it showed up in my office.</p>
      <p>I came to this work in the middle of my life, not the beginning of it, and I think that's part of why it works. I've lived long enough to know how hard it is to be a person, how long a pattern can run before anyone names it, and how much courage it takes to look honestly at your own life. I don't sit across from people as someone who has it all figured out. I sit there as someone who knows the way through, because I've walked it with hundreds of people, and because I'm a person too, still practicing what I teach.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

